<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-923-304  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 923 304.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Reseller News  Nov 13 1989 n341 p117(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The image of things to come: DIP moves from storage, retrieval totransaction-process-oriented applications. (document imageprocessing)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Paradiso, Tony.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Document image processing (DIP) involves capturing and managingoriginal documents as images with the help of page scanners,optical storage media and database managers.andP;  DIP can speed accessto documents and ease the flow of documents through anorganization.andP;  The technology may be one of the most significanttechnological applications that has been seen up until now.andP;  DIPwas developed out of a need to archive and retrieve informationmore efficiently.andP;  Previously, microfiche and microfilm were usedfor this task.andP;  Although currently a niche marketplace, it isanticipated that DIP will become widespread due to the almostlimitless number of ways in which it can be applied.andP;  It isestimated that the DIP market will grow at an impressive rate,with some of the strongest growth coming from the non-dedicatedsystems market, which is estimated to account for $4.2 billion inrevenues in 1992.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     DocumentationImage ProcessingDocument Management SystemsImaging TechnologyInformation Storage and Retrieval.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>